JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 104
IS  - 1
SP  - 121
EP  - 137
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Job market segmentation refers to the idea that there tends to be a correlation among high wages, high productivity, high capital intensity, high value added, few quits relative to layoffs, and low labor turnover. This paper develops a model of wage dispersion and job market segmentation based on the very sparse assumption that the only departure from a strictly orthodox neoclassical world consists of wages being sticky in the short run. Implications of the model are explored and discussed.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
